    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1894-01-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1894-01-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="341" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d341">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Smythe</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Gresham</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince, Haiti</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1894-01-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">January
                                        10, 1894</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>(Received January 24.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 22.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In an interview to-day with the secretary
                            of state for foreign affairs (at his instance) he stated that certain
                            small whalers and other American vessels had been habitually invading
                            Haitian territory, and in the prosecution of their business frequently
                            putting in at closed ports, and presumably carrying on a contraband
                            trade. He stated further, that he desired to give notice to this
                            legation before proceeding to extreme measures. I answered that the U.
                            S. Government could not be expected to patrol Haitian territory, and
                            that the only course open to the Haitian Government in this behalf was
                            to protect its territory in the usual manner, and in that case the only
                            interest of my Government would be to see that the delinquent parties
                            had a fair and impartial trial, in case they proved to be American
                            vessels.</p>
                <p>Since returning to the legation I find the same subject came up some
                            years ago, and that this view (practically) seems to have been sustained
                            by the Department. If my reply needs any modification please advise
                            me.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry M. Smythe.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
